{{italic title}} '''''Harbour Cone from Peggy's Hill''''' (1939) is an early [[oil painting]] by [[New Zealand]] artist [[Colin McCahon]].
{{Infobox artwork | title = Harbour Cone from Peggy's Hill | artist = [[Colin McCahon]] | year = {{start date|1939}} | image = | material = oil on hardwood | subject = [[New Zealand]] landscape | height_metric = 75 | length_metric = 133.3 | condition = Good | city = [[Otago]] | accession = 73/86 | museum = [[Hocken Collections]], Uare Taoka o Hakena, [[University of Otago]] | owner = John & Ethel McCahon Bequest, 1973 }}
== Subject == ''Harbour Cone from Peggy's Hill'' is one of McCahon's earliest explorations of the [[Otago]] region. It depicts an elevated stance from the mountain tops, looking down towards Harbour Cone in the [[Otago Peninsula]]. This work is one of his more realistic creations - showing a clear landscape theme. [[File:Harbour Cone Otago Peninsula.jpg|thumb|Harbour Cone, Otago Peninsula]]
In addition to this exoteric representation, ''Harbour Cone from Peggy's Hill'' also contains more esoteric meanings. McCahon wanted this artwork to express "the concept of nature as a spiritual and redeeming force."<ref name="Spirit">{{cite book|last1=Alderton|first1=Zoe|title=The Spirit of Colin McCahon|date=2015|publisher=Cambridge Scholars Publishing|location=Newcastle upon Tyne|isbn=1-4438-7232-6|page=64}}</ref> In a letter to his friend [[Toss Woollaston]] he explained:
{{Quote|text=I imagined people looking at it then looking at the landscape and for once really seeing it & being happier for it & believing in God & then the brotherhood of men & the futility of war. |author=Colin McCahon to Toss Woollaston (1939)|source=<ref name="Elements of Modernism">{{cite book|last1=Brown|first1=Gordon H.|title=Elements of Modernism in Colin McCahon’s Early Work|date=2003|publisher=Victoria University of Wellington School of Art History, Classics and Religious Studies|location=Wellington|page=34}}</ref>}}
Because of comments such as these, the painting has been read as an evangelical statement designed to connect together God, peace, and the landscape.<ref name="Spirit" />
== Reception == {{Expand section|date=March 2016}} === Early Controversy === '' Harbour Cone from Peggy's Hill '' was behind one of the earliest controversies in McCahon's long career. It was excluded from the 1939 [[Otago Art Society]] exhibition, despite the fact that each member (including McCahon) was entitled to display one work. Linda Tyler believes that this rejection was due to the absence of support "from an interested and informed public."<ref>{{cite book|author1=Tyler, Linda|chapter=A Matter of Taste: Charles Brasch as Art Collector|editor1-last=Kerr|editor1-first=Donald|title=Enduring Legacy: Charles Brasch, Patron, Poet & Collector|date=2003|publisher=University of Otago Press|location=New Zealand|page=49}}</ref>
