{{Infobox artwork | image = Reds Legends of Crosley Field rev.jpg | image_size = 250px | title = Reds Legends of Crosley Field | artist = [[Tom Tsuchiya]] | year = 2003-2004 | type = [[Bronze]] | museum = [[Great American Ball Park]] | city = [[Cincinnati]] }}
'''''Reds Legends of Crosley Field''''' is a group of [[bronze sculptures]] by artist [[Tom Tsuchiya]], located at the main entrance of [[Great American Ball Park]] in [[Cincinnati, Ohio|Cincinnati]], [[Ohio]].<ref name = NYT >{{cite news |work= The New York Times| title=In Baseball’s Bronze Age, Statues are Becoming Bigger Part of the Landscape| date=2011-09-21|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/21/sports/baseball/baseballs-bronze-age.html?pagewanted=all | accessdate=2012-07-19}}</ref><ref name = "Stupp" >Stupp, Dan. ''Opening Day at Great American Ball Park”, p. 58. Sports Publishing L.L.C., 2003. {{ISBN|1-58261-724-4}}</ref> The sculptures represent four [[Crosley Field]] era [[Cincinnati Reds]] players: [[Ted Kluszewski]], [[Ernie Lombardi]], [[Joe Nuxhall]] and [[Frank Robinson]].<ref name= CE >{{cite news| work = The Cincinnati Enquirer|title= Statue of Big Klu big Hit with Little Klu|date =2003-01-04|url=http://reds.enquirer.com/2003/04/01/wwwred1c1.html |accessdate=2012-07-19}}</ref> These players were selected by a fan vote conducted by the Cincinnati Reds.<ref name=MLB>{{cite news| work= Major League Baseball.Com| title= Reds Unveil Nuxhall Statue| date= 2003-07-20| url= http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030720&content_id=436765&vkey=news_cin&fext=.jsp&c_id=cin| accessdate= 2012-07-19| deadurl= yes| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100204223437/http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030720&content_id=436765&vkey=news_cin&fext=.jsp&c_id=cin| archivedate= 2010-02-04| df= }}</ref>
Kluszewski's statue was unveiled on [[Opening Day]], March 31, 2003, to coincide with the official opening of Great American Ball Park. The statues of Nuxhall and Robinson were dedicated in the summer of that year.<ref name=MLB>{{cite news| work= Major League Baseball.Com| title= Reds Unveil Nuxhall Statue| date= 2003-07-20| url= http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030720&content_id=436765&vkey=news_cin&fext=.jsp&c_id=cin| accessdate= 2012-07-19| deadurl= yes| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100204223437/http://cincinnati.reds.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030720&content_id=436765&vkey=news_cin&fext=.jsp&c_id=cin| archivedate= 2010-02-04| df= }}</ref> Subsequently, Lombardi's statue was unveiled in June 28, 2004.<ref name = CN >{{cite news |work= The Cincinnati Enquirer |title= Photo Gallery|date=2004-06-28 | url = http://www.enquirer.com/editions/2004/06/28/reds0627/photomain.html| accessdate=2012-07-20}}</ref>
==Description==
The statues depict the four players interacting with one another in an imaginary ball game at the "Crosley Terrace", a stylized representation of the [[infield]] of [[Crosley Field]].<ref name= CINTI >{{cite news | work= The Cincinnati Enquirer| title= Robinson Hits Cleanup at Crosley Terrace| date=2003-09-26| url= http://reds.enquirer.com/2003/09/26/robinson26.html |accessdate= 2012-07-19}}</ref><ref name = "Pahigian" >[[Josh Pahigian|Pahigian, Josh]], & O’Connell, Kevin. “The Ultimate Baseball Road Trip, 2nd: A Fan's Guide to Major League Stadiums”. P. 201. Lyons Press, 2012. {{ISBN|978-0-7627-7340-4}}</ref> The sculpture group depicts Joe Nuxhall pitching to Frank Robinson, who is swinging the bat at [[home plate]], while Ernie Lombardi crouches behind home plate, ready to catch the ball; and Ted Kluszewski observes the action from the [[on-deck circle]].<ref name = "Pahigian" /> This unique presentation has been praised by both critics and the public alike.<ref name = "Pahigian" /><ref name = WEZ >{{cite news |work= Wezen-Ball|title=Baseball’s Best Statues, Statues by Ballpark|date=2010-03-02|url= http://www.wezen-ball.com/2010-articles/february/baseballs-best-statues-by-ballpark.html | accessdate=2012-07-19}}</ref>
